      ## The Kaggle Compatibility Question

      Numba is actually available on Kaggle — it's pre-installed in their Python
      environment. So this is worth trying seriously, not just in theory.

      The catch is the **first-call compilation overhead.** Numba JIT compiles on the
      first call, which can take 1-5 seconds. In a 500-turn game that's a one-time
      hit on turn 0, but Kaggle's validation episode (bot plays itself) would absorb
      that. After turn 0 the compiled functions run at near-C speed for the remaining
      499 turns.

      You can pre-trigger compilation with a dummy call:

      ```python
      import numba as nb
      import numpy as np

      @nb.njit(cache=True)
      def fast_forward(planet_ships, planet_prod, planet_owner, ...):
      # your simplified forward model
      pass

      # Trigger compilation at import time with dummy data
      _dummy = np.zeros((10, 7), dtype=np.float32)
      fast_forward(_dummy, ...)  # compiles here, not turn 1
      ```

      The `cache=True` flag caches the compiled bytecode to disk so subsequent runs
      don't recompile — though on Kaggle's ephemeral containers this may not persist
      between episodes.

